   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><w>māla</w><w>yo<add>ksi</add></w>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><w><add>śā</add>mn<supplied>a</supplied></w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">to drink alcohol</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">men (?)</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">The Sanskrit text on the fragments (from the Śikhālakasūtra) corresponds to sūtra 135 in the Chinese Madhyamāgama.</note><note type="remarks">The small fragment (<hi>ya[ṃ]ti</hi>) belongs at the beginning of line r.1/a1 (or v.4/b4) of the large fragment. Belongs to the same leaf as SHT 1914.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>surāpānam</hi> 'drinking liquor'. There seem to be no further traces after <hi>[y]o –</hi>. Although several Tocharian glosses on this fragment are deciphered by Schmidt (apud <bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2008"/><citedRange>51</citedRange></bibl>), this gloss has been left unmentioned. As for the glosses deciphered, one of these is (b3) <hi>ānu po ok <hi rend="underline">ra</hi>ṃta<hi rend="underline">r</hi><hi rend="subscript">\</hi></hi> 'übe das Aufhören, [und] du wirst alle acht aufgeben!' ['practice cessation [and] you will give up all eight [of them]!'] (found on the joined fragment SHT 1914). Unfortunately, <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2014"/><citedRange>159</citedRange></bibl> cannot confirm Schmidt's reading; to him, this gloss is essentially illegible.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>(puru)[ṣ](aṃ)</hi> 'man' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2008"/><citedRange>50</citedRange></bibl>). The gloss is found on top of the akṣara <hi>ti</hi> of v4/b4 <hi>(dhva)ṃ(sa)ya[ṃ]ti</hi>, on a loose piece in the frame that directly joins the main fragment.</note></p>
         </div>
