               <item n="m_philcomment_old">&lt;p&gt;The Sanskrit text on the fragments (from the Śikhālakasūtra) corresponds to sūtra 135 in the Chinese Madhyamāgama.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b1.&lt;/b&gt; glosses Skt. &lt;i&gt;surāpānam&lt;/i&gt; 'drinking liquor'. There seem to be no further traces after &lt;i&gt;[y]o –&lt;/i&gt;. Although several Tocharian glosses on this fragment are deciphered by Schmidt (apud [[SHT X]]: 51), this gloss has been left unmentioned. As for the glosses deciphered, one of these is (b3) &lt;i&gt;ānu po ok &lt;u&gt;ra&lt;/u&gt;ṃta&lt;u&gt;r&lt;/u&gt;&lt;sub&gt;\&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/i&gt; 'übe das Aufhören, [und] du wirst alle acht aufgeben!' ['practice cessation [and] you will give up all eight [of them]!'] (found on the joined fragment SHT 1914). Unfortunately, [[Peyrot 2014]]: 159 cannot confirm Schmidt's reading; to him, this gloss is essentially illegible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b3.&lt;/b&gt; glosses Skt. &lt;i&gt;(puru)[ṣ](aṃ)&lt;/i&gt; 'man' ([[SHT X]]: 50). The gloss is found on top of the akṣara &lt;i&gt;ti&lt;/i&gt; of v4/b4 &lt;i&gt;(dhva)ṃ(sa)ya[ṃ]ti&lt;/i&gt;, on a loose piece in the frame that directly joins the main fragment.&lt;/p&gt;</item>
